issue.title: refactor: convert core modules from Flow to TypeScript
issue.body:
# refactor: convert core modules from Flow to TypeScript

## Summary

This PR converts four core module folders from Flow to TypeScript as part of the ongoing TypeScript migration effort:

- `src/core_modules/capture-core/init` (2 files)
- `src/core_modules/capture-core/trackerRedux` (2 files) 
- `src/core_modules/capture-core/cleanUp` (2 files)
- `src/core_modules/capture-core/actions` (6 files)

**Total: 12 files converted**

Key changes include:
- Removed Flow type annotations (`// @flow`) and converted to TypeScript syntax
- Updated `Action` type to include `payload`, `meta`, `error` properties
- Modified `createReducerDescription` function signature to match actual usage patterns
- Made `Updater` type more flexible to handle varying action shapes
- Fixed variable shadowing issues in reducer utility functions

## Review & Testing Checklist for Human

**âš ï¸ High Priority Items:**

- [ ] **Test reducer functionality**: Verify that `createReducerDescription` and related reducer functions work correctly at runtime (this had significant signature changes)
- [ ] **Verify action creators**: Test that action creators in `init.actions.ts` and other converted files produce correct action objects
- [ ] **Check imports**: Ensure all imports work correctly after file renames from `.js` to `.ts`
- [ ] **Local testing**: Run the app locally and test core functionality to catch any runtime errors that TypeScript compilation missed
- [ ] **Regression testing**: Test areas that use the converted modules, particularly working lists and data entry flows

**Recommended test plan:**
1. Start the app locally (`yarn start`)
2. Navigate to different pages that use these core modules
3. Test data entry, working lists, and enrollment functionality
4. Check browser console for any runtime errors

---

### Diagram

```mermaid
%%{ init : { "theme" : "default" }}%%
graph TD
    subgraph "Core Modules Converted"
        InitActions["init/init.actions.ts"]:::major-edit
        InitIndex["init/index.ts"]:::major-edit
        TrackerReducer["trackerRedux/trackerReducer.ts"]:::major-edit
        TrackerIndex["trackerRedux/index.ts"]:::major-edit
        CleanUpActions["cleanUp/cleanUp.actions.ts"]:::major-edit
        CleanUp["cleanUp/cleanUp.ts"]:::major-edit
        ActionsUtils["actions/actions.utils.ts"]:::major-edit
        NavActions["actions/navigateToEnrollmentOverview/navigateToEnrollmentOverview.actions.ts"]:::major-edit
    end
    
    subgraph "External Dependencies"
        Redux["redux"]:::context
        BatchActions["redux-batched-actions"]:::context
        ExistingReducers["Various reducer description files"]:::context
    end
    
    subgraph Legend
        L1[Major Edit]:::major-edit
        L2[Minor Edit]:::minor-edit
        L3[Context/No Edit]:::context
    end
    
    TrackerReducer --> ExistingReducers
    ActionsUtils --> InitActions
    ActionsUtils --> NavActions
    TrackerReducer --> Redux
    TrackerReducer --> BatchActions
    
    classDef major-edit fill:#90EE90
    classDef minor-edit fill:#87CEEB
    classDef context fill:#FFFFFF
```

### Notes


- TypeScript compilation passes with only 2 unrelated errors in existing files
- Linting passes completely after fixing variable shadowing issues
- The `createReducerDescription` function had the most significant changes - its signature was updated to match actual usage patterns found in the codebase
- Used minimalistic conversion approach as requested - avoided adding extensive type definitions
- All original `.js` files were removed and replaced with `.ts` equivalents

**Session Info:**
- Requested by: henrik.vadet@dhis2.org
- Link to Devin run: https://app.devin.ai/sessions/bfaeea9551c14bf48a4390f79f1927a9

issue.body:
## Overview
Prepare for v1.0 release by creating example content, default theme, and comprehensive testing.

## Tasks
- [ ] Create default theme with basic templates
- [ ] Add example content structure and sample posts
- [ ] Implement comprehensive integration tests
- [ ] Performance testing and optimization
- [ ] Security review and vulnerability testing
- [ ] User acceptance testing with real-world scenarios
- [ ] Release notes and changelog preparation
- [ ] Version tagging and release automation

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Default theme works out of the box
- [ ] Example content demonstrates all features
- [ ] Integration tests cover end-to-end scenarios
- [ ] Performance meets design requirements
- [ ] Security scan passes without issues
- [ ] Real users can successfully build sites
- [ ] Release process is documented and tested
- [ ] v1.0 is ready for public use

## Definition of Done
- [ ] All v1.0 features are complete and tested
- [ ] Documentation is comprehensive
- [ ] Performance benchmarks meet targets
- [ ] Security review is complete
- [ ] Release automation works correctly
- [ ] Community feedback is incorporated

## Technical Notes
- Focus on stability and user experience
- Ensure backwards compatibility for future versions
- Document any known limitations
- Plan for post-v1.0 roadmap

## Dependencies
- Requires all previous issues to be completed

Estimated effort: 6-8 days

pull_request.title: Add observer for progress reporting
pull_request.body:
Introduce a new progress reporting interface using observer pattern, while maintaining backward compatibility with the legacy progress_callback (int percent) API.

## Summary by Sourcery

Add a new progress reporting interface based on the observer pattern that emits rich Progress objects for download, parse, and save steps, while preserving the legacy integerâ€callback API with deprecation warnings and ensuring backward compatibility.

New Features:
- Introduce a structured progress reporting API with Progress and ProgressObserver classes for monitoring long-running operations
- Provide a ProgressStatus enum and decorators to attach step, total_steps, and status metadata to progress events
- Maintain backward compatibility by adapting the legacy integer-based progress_callback and issuing deprecation warnings

Enhancements:
- Extend SpecFactory, IODSpecBuilder, DocHandler (XHTML/PDF), and DOMTableSpecParser to emit Progress objects during downloading, parsing, and model saving
- Add utility functions (add_progress_step, offset_progress_steps) to annotate and adjust progress events
- Update mkdocs to include the new progress API documentation

Tests:
- Add comprehensive tests to verify progress_observer functionality, legacy callback adaptation, and correct event sequences across components

         """Report progress if percent changed.
 
-        If the total file size is unknown or invalid, calls the callback with -1 to indicate

+        If the total file size is unknown or invalid, calls the observer with -1 to indicate

comment.body:
**suggestion:** Progress percent calculation may not handle floating point division precisely.

Using int() truncates the value, which may cause missed progress updates, especially for small files. Using round() would improve accuracy.

```suggestion
        percent = -1 if not total or total <= 0 else min(round(downloaded * 100 / total), 100)
```

commits.message:
Solve the Fibonacci sequence with iteration

The function returns 0 and 1 as is, otherwise the following numbers are calculated using the Fibonacci formula, by adding together the previous two numbers in the sequence.

Solve fibonacci with recursion

Recursion was used to find the previous number, which was used to calculate the next number in the sequence. From the recursion, the previous values in the sequence were returned using spread syntax and the next number was added to the sequence until the base case was reached.

Create a mergeSort function that splits arrays

In the function, the arrays are divided in two by recursion until they are only single elements.

Merge sorted arrays

A function was created that merges arrays together using loops that sort numbers from smallest to largest.
